{"cursor":"34052","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox Space mission\n| mission_name = Mercury-Atlas 6 spacecraft_name = Friendship 7 booster = Atlas\n| LV-3B insignia = Friendship 7 insignia.jpg insignia_size = 172px sign =\n| Friendship 7 crew_size = crew = John H. Glenn launch_pad = LC-14 (CCAF) launch\n| = landing = February 20, 1962, 19:43:02 UTC duration = 04:55:23 (hh:mm:ss)\n| orbits = 3 apogee = perigee = period = 88.5 min. inclination = 32.5Â° distance\n| = peakacc = 7.7 g maxvel = mass = crew_photo = Mercury 6, John H Glenn Jr.jpg\n| crew_caption = John Herschel Glenn, Jr. previous = MA-5 next = MA-7\n}}\n\n'Mercury-Atlas 6' (MA-6) was a human spaceflight mission conducted by NASA, the\nspace agency of the United States. As part of Project Mercury, MA-6 was the\nsuccessful first attempt by NASA to place an astronaut into orbit. The MA-6\nmission was launched February 20, 1962. It made three orbits of the Earth,\npiloted by astronaut John Glenn, who became the first American to orbit the\nEarth. The\nSoviet Union had already placed a cosmonaut, Yuri Gagarin, in orbit on Vostok 1\non April 12, 1961 and Gherman Titov on August 6, 1961 The\ntwo previous Americans in space, Alan Shepard and Gus Grissom had flown sub-\norbital missions. The event was named an IEEE Milestone in\n2011.\n\nThe Mercury spacecraft, named 'Friendship 7', was carried to orbit by an Atlas\nLV-3B launch vehicle lifting off from Launch Complex 14 at Cape Canaveral,\nFlorida. After four hours and 56 minutes in flight the spacecraft re-entered the\nEarth's atmosphere, splashed down in the Atlantic Ocean and was safely taken\naboard the USS ''Noa''.\n","linknr":510,"url":"Mercury-Atlas_6","recorded":1362267824,"links":52,"instances":["rotation","weapon","spacecraft_landing"],"pdf":["http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/history/mercury/ma-6/docs/ma-6-results.pdf","http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19930074071_1993074071.pdf","http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19990026158_1999028570.pdf","http://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19630011968_1963011968.pdf"],"categories":["1962 in spaceflight","Human spaceflights","Mercury program","Individual spacecraft in the collection of the Smithsonian Institution","Spacecraft which reentered in 1962"],"headings":["Crew","Preparation","Flight","Spacecraft location","Timeline and parameters","Anniversary commemoration","See also","Notes","References","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/83/Friendship_7_insignia.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d8/Mercury_6%2C_John_H_Glenn_Jr.jpg/200px-Mercury_6%2C_John_H_Glenn_Jr.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4e/Mercury_insignia.jpg/32px-Mercury_insignia.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Aurora_7_patch.png/34px-Aurora_7_patch.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Glenn_Enters_his_Mercury_Capsule_-_GPN-2000-001029.jpg/220px-Glenn_Enters_his_Mercury_Capsule_-_GPN-2000-001029.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Launch_of_Friendship_7_-_GPN-2000-000686.jpg/250px-Launch_of_Friendship_7_-_GPN-2000-000686.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Mercury-Atlas_6_Earth_photo.jpg/250px-Mercury-Atlas_6_Earth_photo.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Glenn62.jpg/250px-Glenn62.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6c/Mercury_Friendship7_Bassett_Celestia.jpg/250px-Mercury_Friendship7_Bassett_Celestia.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.or